South African Equities: BHP Billiton, Naspers, SacOil, Basil Read, Sasol

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a   a n d   R e n e e   B o n o r c h i s
-- 
2011-04-11T16:20:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-11/south-african-stocks-retreat-bhp-billiton-don-naspers-sasol-are-active.html
South Africa’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index advanced 8.16, or 0.02 percent, to 32,814.43 at the
5 p.m. close in Johannesburg, a second day of gains.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
South African market today.  Basil Read Holdings Ltd. (BSR)  , a construction and
engineering company, dropped 12 cents, or 0.9 percent, to 12.65
rand, the most since March 24. The company said TWP Holdings
Ltd., the business it bought in 2009, failed to achieve targeted
earnings, meaning that a deferred payment will not be paid to
TWP shareholders.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, increased to a two-month high, jumping 6.40 rand, or
2.3 percent, to 287.10 rand. BHP successfully completed a $6.3
billion buyback at A$40.85 per share, it said in a regulatory
announcement today. The company also doused speculation it plans
to buy Royal Dutch Shell Plc’s stake in Woodside Petroleum Ltd.
and make a A$46 billion ($48.6 billion) takeover.  The  Don Group (DON)  Ltd, a hotel operator, rose the
most in a week, gaining 1 cent, or 4.8 percent, to 22 cents. The
company said it’s in talks that may affect its share price if
successfully concluded.  Naspers Ltd. (NPN)  , Africa’s largest media company,
retreated the most this month, declining 8.55 rand, or 2.2
percent, to 376.33 rand.  Tencent Holdings Ltd. (700) , Naspers’ largest
single asset by value and  China ’s biggest social networking
Internet company, fell the most in two weeks after Sohu.com
reported Facebook Inc. signed an agreement with Baidu Inc. to
set up a social-networking website in China.  SacOil Holdings Ltd. (SCL SJ), an oil and natural gas
exploration company, dropped for a second day, losing 13 cents,
or 6.5 percent, to 1.86 rand. The company plans to raise further
capital to fund current and future operations, it said in a
regulatory filing today.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, dropped for a third day, losing 10.05 rand, or
2.5 percent, to 386.95 rand. Oil fell from a 30-month high in
 New York  after the  International Monetary Fund  cut its growth
forecasts for the U.S. and  Japan .  To contact the reporters on this story:
